{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94d50304-889a-49dc-a1e1-104a94cd2b99","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nAfter a SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may lag behind the new SDK version. `dotnet workload update` pulls the latest workload manifests and packages that match your current SDK.\n\n`dotnet workload repair` only *reinstalls* the existing workload versions — it fixes corrupted installs but won't bring them up to date with a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n| Scenario | Command |\n|----------|---------|\n| Workloads out of date after SDK update | `dotnet workload update` |\n| Workload files corrupted/missing | `dotnet workload repair` |\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-windows`, etc.) is installed, and check `dotnet --info` to verify the active SDK version matches your project's `global.json` (if present).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0d266b1a-4008-4940-9176-1c630d11ea00","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` to fix their .NET MAUI build issue after a SDK update. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.\n\nLet me answer based on my knowledge of .NET workloads:\n\n- `dotnet workload update` - Updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the SDK version you're using. This is what you want when workloads are out of date relative to a new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` - Reinstalls all installed workloads. This fixes corrupted installations but doesn't update versions.\n\n\n- Since the user updated their .NET SDK, the workloads need to be updated to match the new SDK version, so `dotnet workload update` is the right approach here.","outputTokens":426,"requestId":"E854:1EDE:22F496:297B96:69F93E5E"},"id":"a9021e9e-cde4-4f00-a9ed-64f51422644c","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:48:41.037Z","parentId":"6c3942ac-563d-465c-99cd-5aa94a997c08"}
